description.narrative:
The project title “Assistance to the newly arrived Central African Refugees in Garoua Boulai and Gada subdivision in the East Region of Cameroon” will be implemented in Garoua Boulai and Gado in East region from 05 February to 22 March 2021 within 45 days. 

The project aims to improved living condition of 6775 central African Refugees and host community (5 655 refugees and 1120 host community peoples) through the&#58;
-  Distribution of NFI kits (household items or cocking items, clothing, blankets, mosquito nets.) to 1999 households;
- Set up of hand washing facilities in public spaces;
- Hygiene promotion/ awareness raising campaigns on Wash and COVID 19 prevention (Door to Door);
- Distribution of wash kits (buckets, jerry cans, cups, soaps, 20 liter canisters) to 1999 households;
- PDM activities and
- Set up a feedback Mechanism

The project will be carried out in collaboration with beneficiaries and all partners. In order to make sure that activities are well implemented, Plan will continuous to attend in weekly Coordination meetings where their realisation and challenges will be shared. Government partners will be frequently informed of Plan's Intervention even the challenge in order to facilitate the interventions. A feedback mechanism will be set up in order to make sure that beneficiaries are fully engaged, their need is addressed and Do No Harm Principle is respected.

Gender&#58; This humanitarians’ intervention has targeted different groups of vulnerable people including Women, men, boys and girls.  In terms of gender and coordination, the goal is to ensure that a quality and effective response is done considering the specific groups (households lead by women and young boys or girls, men and boys). Advocacy will be made in coordination meeting and coordination platforms in order to respond to the needs per gender (women, girls, boys and men). Actions will be taken to ensure participation of different groups, women, men, girls and boys in the coordination meetings with leader's committees, government actors and NGOs in the field.

The intervention aims at the first emergency response to provide protective, inclusive, safe and continued quality education for Covid-19 and conflict affected children in NE Nigeria. The project will achieve improved access for girls/boys to equitable inclusive education and learning opportunities in critical time of interruption of schooling due to crisis and ensure key messages delivered to target beneficiaries on how to protect from Covid-19 and continue quality and relevance of formal and non-formal education through awareness, key advocacy messages, alternative education approaches and back to learning&#58;

Expected results&#58;
1.	Help to prevent the spread and transmission of COVID-19 amongst learners of ECD, basic, junior and senior secondary schools, teachers, parents and SBMCs;
2.	Mitigate/Minimize the impact of school closure due to COVID19 on learning and wellbeing of learners, teachers, parents and SBMC through alternatives solution;
3.	Ensure effective, inclusive and safe return to quality learning for learners, teachers, and SBMC members;
4.	Networking with State and LGA level Government Officials on Covid-19 Response.

This project aims to&#58; 
1) Provide essential supplies like masks, sensitizers, hand gloves, glasses, shoes, soaps, detergents/cleaning materials- education supplies to children and teachers in 100 schools to 20,400 learners (9180 girls and 11,220 boys)
2) Provide incentives for home schooling and capacity building for 624 teachers (220 females and 304 males) and 800 SBMC members/Parents (320 females and 480 males) on Covid, WASH and PSS;
3) Development, printing and distribution of appropriate awareness raising materials (i.e. posters, leaflets, comics), radio messages, SMS/Text messages, social media and SUBEBs/MoEs websites on coronavirus prevention and referrals procedures in the local language to reach to 41,804 individuals (19,380 females and 23,064 males) 
4) Procure educational supplies for 20,400 students for back to learning and work with SUBEBs/MoEs on safe reopening of schools

To respond to the immediate humanitarian needs of Older People through community-based programme covering the sectors of Health, WASH and Protection and targeted support to OP in accessing humanitarian services generally. However, this project will more focus on strengthening the Age and Disability task force according to DFID. However, on March 11, 2020, considering the alarming levels of spread and severity and by the alarming levels of inaction, WHO declared the coronavirus (COVID-19) sweeping across the world is a pandemic. According to the research findings done by Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention, Older People are in the riskiest position. From the report, it is found out that ages from 50-59: 1.3%, 60-69: 3.6%, 70-79: 8% and 80 and over: 14.8% are COVID-19 mortality rates by age. The overall mortality rate estimated by researchers was 2.3%, but experts caution that it is likely exaggerated due to milder cases that have gone uncounted. On March 08, 2020, Institute of Epidemiology Disease Control and Research authorities had confirmed three patients of Covid-19 in Bangladesh. Considering the importance, humanitarian response principles, global community demand and organizational mandate, the project proposed to initiate every necessary actions for responding to coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak. To address this crucial issue, project requests for extra funds as well. 

The following key activities will be included for creating awareness – 
1. Audio message broadcasting at AFS level and miking in the host community and one to one and small group counselling and SBCC materials distribution; 
2. Providing masks, hand sanitizers, medical gowns, disposable gowns, hand gloves, goggles and shoes to service providers specially doctors, paramedics, physiotherapists and psychosocial counsellors; 
3. Distribute hand-washing materials like Soap, cleaning and disinfection materials and mask (need-based)  to the older people and their families; 
4. Awareness building on hand washing procedures; 
5. Install hand-washing amenities at the entrance of the Age Friendly Spaces and cleaning and sterilize the office and service premises; 
6. Temperature checking for older people at AFS level and homebased/ mobile services; 
7. Orient all staff and community volunteers on Coronavirus disease (COVID-19); 
8. Providing screening kits and other equipment to the Government service proviers 
9. Supporting (transport, accompaniment and treatment) to the suspected/infected person
